hants, factory workers, marketers, and even baseball players, jazz musicians, and sex workers. Through their stories, Cigarettes, Inc. accounts for the cigarette’s spectacular rise in popularity and in the process offers nothing less than a sweeping reinterpretation of corporate power itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aBritish American Tobacco Company-History. 0aBritish-American Tobacco Co. (China)-History. 0aCigarette industryzChinaxHistory. 0aCigarette industryzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aCigarette industry-China-History. 0aCigarette industry-United States-History. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aChina.  aUnited States.  abright leaf tobaco.  acigarette.  acorporation.  aempire.  aglobal.  amodernity.  asegregation.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311068858040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226533452423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226533452/original  a978-3-11-068858-0  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles